[4] Suspected, research

3 Jul 2015: Ghana launches public campaign on safety of Ebola vaccine trial
http://www.coastweek.com/3827-focus-10.htm

5 Jul 2015 Ghana: Doubts over integrity of Ebola trials
http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Doubts-over-integrity-of-Ebola-trials-366573
[The public outcry against the Ebola vaccine trials in Ghana has abated. There are still unanswered questions, however.
The main concerns raised by the Technical Committee of the Academy relate to the following:
"1. Uncertainties about the appropriateness of the vaccine, including:
a. The nature and origins of the Ebola virus, including the circumstances of its appearance in Guinea;
b. Whether the Zaire strain of the virus, which is the one being used in the GSK vaccine to be tested in Ghana, is the strain responsible for the Ebola epidemics in Liberia, Mali, Nigeria, Senegal and Sierra Leone, and
c. The identity and characteristics of other strains of the Ebola virus that might exist;
2. The use in the GSK/NIH vaccine of a gene particle of the wild species of the Zaire Ebola virus, rather than the gene particle of the Makona strain isolated in the epidemic in Guinea;
3. What pre-clinical animal experimentations had been carried out with a vaccine based on the Makona strain to establish evidence of safety, immunogenicity and protection; ... - more"
[It appears that a dialog between scientists and the community is needed to allay fears as much as possible. - Mod.LK]

1 Jul 2015 Liberia: China cautious as Ebola returns to Liberia
http://citizentv.co.ke/news/china-cautious-as-ebola-returns-to-liberia/
[The commander of the Chinese peacekeeping contingent called on all its 558 members to upgrade prevention and control levels. Personnel in protective suits have also thoroughly sterilized the contingent's base.

According to He Long, the commander: "We've launched an emergency plan in response to the new Ebola case. All officers must wear masks, gloves and protective suits before going out on missions. All vehicles must be sterilized upon return to the camp, while officers must sterilize their hands and shoes and have their temperatures taken," said He Long, the commander."]

2 Jul 2015 Liberia: UPDATE 2-Liberia investigating animal link after Ebola re-emerges
http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/02/health-ebola-liberia-idUSL8N0ZI1WB20150702?rpc=401
[According to Dr Moses Massaquoi, case management team leader for Liberia's Ebola task force, the 3 villagers who tested Ebola-positive ate dog meat together. Some locals said the deceased patient and others in the village had recently dug up and eaten a dead dog.

There is concern about the possibility of domestic animals being able to carry the virus. Fruit bats of the Pteropodidae family are known to serve as Ebola virus reservoirs.

Dr Moses Massaquoi, case management team leader for Liberia's Ebola task force, said that an investigation by the response team is underway to discover whether domestic animals might be carrying the virus, he said, referencing mysterious deaths of hundreds of cattle in remote Lofa County, which is in the northern-most portion of Liberia.

According to Ben Neuman, a virologist and Ebola expert at Reading University (UK), a possible cause of the virus resurgence could be from survivors carrying small parts of the virus in their bodies, which has reactivated the disease.

Another cause of the new Ebola cases in Liberia could be by sexual transmission, due to the persistence in semen for up to 90 days. [ProMED-mail Rapporteur Joe Dudley]

[Antibody prevalence in 15 of the 99 dogs sampled in Mekambo (15.2 percent prevalence rate).
For the full reference on Ebola virus antibody in dogs, see Allela L(1), Boury O, Pouillot R, et al. Ebola virus antibody prevalence in dogs and human risk. Emerg Infect Dis. 2005 Mar;11(3):385-90.
Abstract. During the 2001-2002 outbreak in Gabon, we observed that several dogs were highly exposed to Ebola virus by eating infected dead animals. To examine whether these animals became infected with Ebola virus, we sampled 439 dogs and screened them by Ebola virus-specific immunoglobulin (Ig) G assay, antigen detection, and viral polymerase chain reaction amplification. Seven (8.9 percent) of 79 samples from the 2 main towns, 15 (15.2 percent) of 99 samples from Mekambo, and 40 (25.2 percent) of 159 samples from villages in the Ebola virus-epidemic area had detectable Ebola virus-IgG, compared to only 2 (2 percent) of 102 samples from France. Among dogs from villages with both infected animal carcasses and human cases, seroprevalence was 31.8 percent. A significant positive direct association existed between seroprevalence and the distances to the Ebola virus-epidemic area. This study suggests that dogs can be infected by Ebola virus and that the putative infection is asymptomatic.]

2 Jul 2015 Liberia: Ebola in Liberia--2 more cases confirmed as rumors of 2nd patient zero spread
http://www.breitbart.com/national-security/2015/07/02/ebola-in-liberia-two-more-cases-confirmed-as-rumors-of-second-patient-zero-spread/
[The 17-year-old young man who died of Ebola virus disease on 28 Jun 2015 may actually be a 2nd index case and not the victim of the Ebola outbreak that began in February 2014.]

2 Jul 2015 Liberia: Tracing 100 suspected carriers after 2nd Ebola death
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507021503.html?viewall=1
[A village neighbor said 2 people and a pregnant woman also ate the dog meat. Both people are still at large.

The Unification Town Clinic -- which backs onto the runway of Liberia's international airport, and is where the case was treated for a diagnosis of malaria prior to his death -- was quarantined. About 30 meters (100 feet) away from Unification Town Clinic, a security guard stands at the metal gate through which one may access the airport runway. There is a chlorine bucket by his side.

Workers from the Global Communities visited the clinic one Wed 1 Jul 2015 to disinfest the facility. A friend of the case was treated at another clinic, Charlesville clinic.]

[The 2 other young men who also ate the dog must have been told that a dog was buried there and that it died of an unidentified illness. - Mod.JW]

2 Jul 2015: Liberia officials restart Ebola monitoring after new outbreak
http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-02/liberia-officials-restart-ebola-monitoring-after-new-outbreak
[Update: There are 2 confirmed and 2 suspected Ebola cases. About 175 people are being monitored.]

2 Jul 2015: Liberia to host soccer, Ebola ban lifted
