2 Jul 2015 Liberia: Ebola Prompts efforts to boost condom use in Liberia
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507020635.html?viewall=1]
[The campaign, launched by the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) and partners, aims to reach 1.5 million Liberians with condoms and related information.]

2 Jul 2015 Liberia: New Ebola cases in Liberia raise fears of fresh outbreak
<http://www.euronews.com/2015/07/02/new-ebola-cases-in-liberia-raise-fears-of-fresh-outbreak/
[The village of Nedowein, the home of the deceased 17-year-old young man, has been placed under quarantine. Health officials, wearing boots and rubber gloves, went house-to-house informing the residents of the order to remain in their homes. According to Cestus Tarpeh, a health authority spokesperson in Margibi County, the 2 new cases had been in contact with him. According to Dr. Moses Massaquoi, case management team leader for Liberia's Ebola task force, the people under surveillance include 14 health workers who have placed themselves in quarantine.

Also see http://sentinelrepublic.com/liberia-quarantines-community-where-corpse-tested-for-ebola-san-diego-6/19471/. It is noteworthy that Liberians proceeded correctly upon learning of the case. The teenager's parents called the national Ebola hotline the day their son died, and a "safe burial team," whose members wear full protective gear and are trained to handle bodies infected with Ebola, buried him that day, [Deputy Health Minister Tolbert] Nyenswah said. - Mod.LK]

3 Jul 2015 Liberia: Ebola - As virus resurfaces in Liberia, UNICEF teams and supplies arrive in affected areas
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507031638.html?viewall=1
[The United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) has begun distributing emergency supplies in the affected communities including tents for isolating those under quarantine, hygiene kits and chlorine and buckets for hand-washing stations. To minimize the risk of further infections and to protect and assist those affected in Margibi County, apparently the site of the index case for this outbreak, UNICEF social mobilization teams are on the ground conducting door-to-door awareness campaigns on Ebola prevention. In the next few days, the facility where the victim attended school will be decontaminated, new hygiene stations will be set up, and soap and chlorine distributed. UNICEF and Liberia's government will work to ensure anti-Ebola measures (i.e., taking the temperatures of the students before they enter the school) will be followed.]

5 Jul 2015 Liberia: Ebola Resurgence under Control, Liberia Assures Nigeria
http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/ebola-resurgence-under-control-liberia-assures-nigeria/213909/

2 Jul 2015 Nigeria: Ebola - Nigerian government raises alert level across states
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507020387.html?viewall=1
[Because of the reappearance of the Ebola virus disease in Liberia, the Nigerian government has raised the alert level, and now includes all of its states.]

3 Jul 2015 UK: Patient admitted to Liverpool hospital for Ebola testing
http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-07-03/patient-admitted-to-liverpool-hospital-for-ebola-testing/
[According to Dr Deborah Turbitt, Ebola National Incident Director at Public Health England, "Public Health England can confirm a patient has been admitted to Royal Liverpool University Hospital and is currently undergoing a series of tests, one of which is for Ebola. Ebola is considered very unlikely, but testing will take place as a precaution, as is our usual practice in these circumstances." [The patient has a history of travel in West Africa.]

But according to news on 5 Jul 2015: "UK: Ebola scare: Patient admitted to Royal Liverpool hospital tests negative for deadly virus."
http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/ebola-scare-patient-admitted-royal-9587783

